---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "GST Complete Guide 2024: GST Rates, Calculator, Filing & Compliance for India";
const description = "Complete GST guide for India. Learn about GST rates (5%, 12%, 18%, 28%), GST calculator, GST filing process, input tax credit, GST compliance, and latest GST council updates for FY 2024-25.";
const image = "/images/blogs/gst-complete-guide.jpg";
const author = "Kira Tanaka";
const lastUpdated = "July 2026";
const readTime = "15 min read";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} image={image}>
  <div class="min-h-screen bg-canvas dark:bg-primary">
    <main class="min-h-screen">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-6 text-sm">
          <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><a href="/" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Home</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted" aria-hidden="true">/</span><a href="/blogs" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Tax Guides</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted" aria-hidden="true">/</span><span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary" aria-current="page">GST Complete Guide</span></li>
          </ol>
        </nav>

        <article class="prose max-w-none">
          <header class="mb-8">
            <img src="/images/blogs/gst-complete-guide.jpg" alt="GST complete guide for India" class="mb-6 w-full rounded-lg object-cover max-h-64" />
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">{title}</h1>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-4 text-sm text-muted dark:text-muted">
              <span>By <span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary">{author}</span></span>
              <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
              <span>Last updated: {lastUpdated}</span>
              <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
              <span>{readTime}</span>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-4 flex items-center gap-3">
              <img src="/images/avatars/kira-tanaka.jpg" alt="Kira Tanaka" class="h-10 w-10 rounded-full object-cover" />
              <div>
                <p class="text-sm font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Kira Tanaka</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-muted dark:text-muted">GST & Indirect Tax Specialist</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-4 rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary">
              <p class="text-sm text-body dark:text-muted"><strong>Editorial Review:</strong> This guide has been reviewed for accuracy against current GST rules and rates as updated by the GST Council for FY 2024-25.</p>
            </div>
          </header>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Goods and Services Tax (GST) is a comprehensive, multi-stage, destination-based indirect tax levied on every value addition. Implemented in India on July 1, 2017, GST replaced multiple indirect taxes including Value Added Tax (VAT), Service Tax, Excise Duty, and Octroi. This unified tax system has simplified indirect taxation and created a common national market.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">What is GST?</h2>
            <p>GST is a single indirect tax on the supply of goods and services, right from the manufacturer to the consumer. It is a destination-based tax, meaning the tax is collected by the state where the goods or services are consumed. GST follows a dual model: Central GST (CGST) levied by the Central Government and State GST (SGST) levied by State Governments on intra-state supplies. For inter-state supplies, Integrated GST (IGST) is collected by the Central Government.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">GST Rate Structure</h2>
            <p>GST in India is structured into four main tax slabs, with special rates for certain categories:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li><strong>0% Rate:</strong> Essential items including fresh food grains, milk, eggs, fruits, vegetables, salt, and educational services.</li>
              <li><strong>5% Rate:</strong> Common-use items such as sugar, tea, coffee, edible oils, spices, and processed food items.</li>
              <li><strong>12% Rate:</strong> Items including processed foods, mobile phones, computers, and certain business services.</li>
              <li><strong>18% Rate:</strong> The most common rate, applied to electronics, furniture, personal care products, and professional services.</li>
              <li><strong>28% Rate:</strong> Luxury items and sin goods including cars, tobacco products, aerated drinks, and high-end electronics.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>A special rate of 3% applies to gold and precious stones. Additionally, cesses such as the compensation cess apply on top of the 28% rate for certain goods like tobacco products.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Input Tax Credit (ITC)</h2>
            <p>Input Tax Credit is one of the most important features of GST, allowing businesses to claim credit for the GST paid on inputs used in the supply of goods or services. This eliminates the cascading effect of taxes that existed under the pre-GST regime.</p>
            <p>To claim ITC, the following conditions must be met:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>The supplier must have filed their GST returns.</li>
              <li>The recipient must have received the goods or services.</li>
              <li>The tax invoice, debit note, or other taxable document must be available.</li>
              <li>The supplier must have paid the tax to the government.</li>
              <li>The recipient must file their return on or before the due date.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">GST Compliance and Filing</h2>
            <p>GST compliance involves several periodic returns that businesses must file:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li><strong>GSTR-1:</strong> Monthly return for outward supplies (sales). Due on the 11th of the following month.</li>
              <li><strong>GSTR-2A:</strong> Auto-generated statement for inward supplies (purchases), automatically populated from supplier filings.</li>
              <li><strong>GSTR-3B:</strong> Monthly summary return summarizing outward supplies, inward supplies, and tax payment. Due on the 20th of the following month.</li>
              <li><strong>GSTR-9:</strong> Annual return, due on December 31 of the following financial year.</li>
              <li><strong>GSTR-9C:</strong> Annual reconciliation statement, due by December 31, mandatory for taxpayers with turnover exceeding ₹2 crore.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">GST Interest and Late Fees</h2>
            <p>Late payment of GST attracts interest at 18% per annum from the due date of payment. Late filing of GSTR-3B attracts a late fee of ₹50 per day (₹20 per day for nil returns) for each state or union territory. Late filing of GSTR-1 attracts the same late fee structure. Taxpayers should ensure timely compliance to avoid accumulating interest and penalties.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Who Should Register for GST?</h2>
            <p>GST registration is mandatory for businesses with an annual turnover exceeding the threshold limits: ₹20 lakh for regular states and ₹10 lakh for special category states (northeastern states and Jammu & Kashmir). Even if your turnover is below the threshold, voluntary registration is available and offers benefits such as input tax credit eligibility and the ability to sell across state lines.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Conclusion</h2>
            <p>GST has fundamentally transformed India's indirect tax landscape, creating a unified national market and simplifying compliance. Understanding GST rates, calculation methods, and filing requirements is essential for any business operating in India. Use our <a href="/countries/india/gst/gst-calculator">GST calculator</a> to compute GST amounts accurately and stay updated with the latest rates and council decisions. For more details, explore our <a href="/countries/india">India tax overview</a> and other educational resources.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-hairline bg-canvas-soft p-6 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary" aria-label="Related calculators">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">Related Calculators</h3>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <a href="/countries/india/gst/gst-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">India GST Calculator</a>
            <a href="/countries/india/income-tax/income-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">India Income Tax Calculator</a>
            <a href="/countries/india/tds/tds-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">India TDS Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>
</Layout>